we can't use the existing Chrome profile's cookies...\n\nLet me try yet another approach: use `npx` to download and use `chrome-cookies-secure` or use a JS script that directly accesses the cookies database with a bundled sqlite.\n\nActually, there's a built-in Windows tool called `cscript` or I could write a PowerShell script to copy the cookie database and use a COM object...\n\nNo, let me just take the most straightforward approach:\n\n1. Use `npm install better-sqlite3` temporarily to read the Chrome cookie database\n2. Then try to decrypt using chrome's encryption key\n\nOr even better - let me use the `edge-paths` approach. Actually...\n\nLet me try the SIMPLEST approach possible: write a Node.js script that uses `child_process` to run SQLite from a source that can just use a built-in Node SQLite library. Since `better-sqlite3` isn't installed, let me try `npx` to temporarily use a tool.\n\nWait actually, I just recalled that Windows has a tool called `Microsoft.Data.Sqlite` but that's .NET. There's no built-in SQLite on Windows.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Instead of reading Chrome's cookie database directly, let me:\n\n1. Close Chrome (done)\n2. Write a C# script to use Microsoft.Data.Sqlite or System.Data.SQLite\n3. Or... use a PowerShell approach\n\nActually, the easiest approach that will definitely work:\n\n1. Use Playwright's bundled Chromium (without `channel: 'chrome'`)\n2. `launchPersistentContext` with a fresh temp profile\n3. Use the `addCookies` to add cookies... but we need the cookies first\n\nOK, I think the simplest practical approach is:\n\n1. Write a small PowerShell script that copies just the Cookies database file\n2. Install `better-sqlite3` or use `sql.js` (which is pure JS, no native bindings needed)  \n3. Read and decrypt the cookies\n\nOr let me try yet another approach - use `npx @cliqz/adblocker-electron` no that's not right.\n\nActually, let me try the simplest thing: use `npm explore` or npx to run `chrome-cookies-secure` which is a npm package that can extract Chrome cookies.\n\nLet me try:\n```\nnpx chrome-cookies-secure\n```\n\nActually, let me just try a pragmatic approach with what's available. I'll write a script that reads the Chrome Local State to get the encryption key, then reads the cookies SQLite database.\n\nWait, I have another idea. The Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP) can be used to connect to a running Chrome instance. But Chrome needs to be started with `--remote-debugging-port` flag. Since I just killed Chrome, I can restart it with that flag.\n\nBut the user said \"已关闭chrome\" so they might have intentionally closed it...\n\nOK let me just try the most straightforward thing: write a Node script that uses `sql.js` (pure JS SQLite, no native deps) to read the cookie database.\n\n```javascript\nimport initSqlJs from 'sql.js';\n// or require\n```\n\nHmm that's a package. Let me check what npm packages are globally installed.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_4m2FuHmm109F1J5NnsNw9890","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"npm list -g --depth=0 2>$null"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":246,"output":1162,"cacheRead":36480,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37888,"cost":{"input":0.00003444,"output":0.00032536,"cacheRead":0.00102144,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00138124}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779249548456,"responseId":"050d4e06-2dcb-477c-95cc-89c8f0c4549d"}}
