{"type":"message","id":"50bae7f4","parentId":"00421e73","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:02:11.499Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The cookies in the temp profile don't have a valid session anymore - it went to the login page. This means the previous copy worked because the cookies were fresh, but now Chrome has been writing to the profile (from the previous script launch) which might have invalidated things.\n\nWait, actually the previous script deleted the temp profile. So I re-copied and ran again, but this time the session cookie expired or was invalid. That's odd - the tapdsession was valid until 2026/5/27.\n\nActually, the issue might be that the temp profile was used by the previous script (first run), which created Chrome user data files. Although the script deleted the temp directory in the finally block, maybe the `context.close()` already invalidated the session or something.\n\nHmm, but I re-copied from the original. Maybe the original Chrome profile no longer has a valid session because when Chrome was killed earlier, the session state changed.\n\nOr maybe copying the profile while Chrome is not running vs while it was running makes a difference. The first copy was made after I killed Chrome. The second copy was made after Chrome was launched again (by the first script). But the parent (original) profile wasn't modified by Playwright.\n\nActually, looking at the date: it's 2026-05-20 11:56. The tapdsession was created at approximately this time. The first extraction happened at around 12:00 and the cookie was valid. Now at approximately 12:02, it's showing login page.\n\nWait, let me think about this differently. The temp profile was re-copied from the ORIGINAL Chrome profile that 周以天 logged into. But the original Chrome profile was launched with `--remote-debugging-port=9222` by my Start-Process command earlier (which may have failed to actually start with that port properly). Chrome processes were running, which means the original profile might have been modified.\n\nActually, after the first extraction ran successfully, the script deleted the temp profile. But the original Chrome profile is still intact. When I kill Chrome and re-copy, the original should still have the cookies.\n\nLet me check: the first extraction was successful and got tapdsession. So the cookies are there. But the second extraction went to login page. This could be because:\n\n1. The tapdsession expired between the two runs (unlikely, expires in a week)\n2. The cookie wasn't properly copied to the temp profile\n3. The copy happened at a bad time\n\nActually, I think the issue is simpler. After the first `extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs` ran, Chrome was launched by Playwright using the temp profile. The original Chrome profile (where 周以天 logged in) was already killed at 11:59. The temp profile then ran and the user might have been prompted to login, and we didn't. But the FIRST extraction successfully got the cookie.\n\nWait no, the first extraction is what succeeded with 5 cookies. The second extraction (extract_tapd_cookies_full.mjs) is the one that's currently showing the login page. This is a fresh copy from the original profile.\n\nLet me cancel the current running one and do a cleaner approach. The first extraction already gave us the tapdsession cookie, which is the most critical one. Let me check if that works for actual TAPD requests.\n\nActually, let me think again about what cookies we need. The previous tapd_cookies.json had many cookies including `t_u`, `_t_crop`, `_t_uid`, `t_cloud_login`. These might be important for identifying the user. Let me kill the current process and try yet another approach.\n\nActually, wait. Maybe the issue is that the temp copy doesn't have the `Network/Cookies` file properly copied, or the encryption key doesn't match. The `Local State` file contains the encryption key that's DPAPI-encrypted, and Chrome decrypts it when reading cookies. On the same machine, DPAPI should still work with the copied files because DPAPI is machine-level.\n\nLet me kill the current process and try the first script again (which worked), but also check for more cookies.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_iMwr7kzBd74axqvcrDez0856","name":"process","arguments":{"sessionId":"faint-atlas","action":"kill"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":206,"output":939,"cacheRead":45184,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46329,"cost":{"input":0.000028840000000000002,"output":0.00026292000000000004,"cacheRead":0.001265152,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0015569120000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779249715797,"responseId":"f143ef28-7011-4c6e-b535-aa928385d7c4"}}
