{"type":"message","id":"ba77be64","parentId":"9e4e3a96","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:04:09.360Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still 0 cookies! This is very frustrating. The full profile is copied (458MB, 4266 files) including the Cookies database. But Playwright's `launchPersistentContext` reads 0 cookies.\n\nThis must mean that Playwright's bundled Chromium cannot read Chrome's encrypted cookies. The reason is:\n1. Chrome uses AES-256-GCM to encrypt cookies\n2. The encryption key is stored in `Local State` under `os_crypt.encrypted_key`\n3. This key is itself encrypted with Windows DPAPI\n4. When Chromium starts and tries to read the cookies database, it tries to:\n   a. Read the encrypted key from Local State\n   b. Decrypt it using DPAPI\n   c. Use the decrypted key to decrypt each cookie value\n5. Step (b) should work because DPAPI is tied to the Windows user account, not the Chrome profile\n6. But maybe Chromium (Playwright's bundled version) handles DPAPI differently than Chrome\n\nWait, actually, when using `launchPersistentContext` with a Chrome profile and the default settings, Playwright launches its bundled Chromium, NOT the system Chrome. The `channel: 'chrome'` option is required to launch system Chrome, and we removed it because it was causing issues.\n\nBut the bundled Chromium might use a different version of Chrome's encryption and may not be compatible with the cookie format.\n\nHowever, the first successful run (extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs) DID find cookies. But that script also did NOT use `channel: 'chrome'`. So how did it work?\n\nHmm, let me re-read the first successful run more carefully...\n\n```\n[1/3] Navigating to TAPD...\nCurrent URL: https://www.tapd.cn/\n[2/3] Found 5 TAPD cookies\n✅ tapdsession: 17792496444cacb6af68c19f3f34be...\n   Expires: 2026/5/27 12:00:44\n[3/3] ✅ Saved 5 cookies to tapd_cookies.json\n```\n\nWait, the first run navigated to TAPD first (before reading cookies). When it navigated, the Chromium browser loaded the page and exchanged cookies with the server, which populated the in-memory cookie jar. So the cookies came from the navigation HTTP exchange, not from reading the database.\n\nThat's the key insight! `context.cookies()` returns the cookies that the browser has in its in-memory store for the current browsing session. When the browser first starts, it loads cookies from the database. But if it can't decrypt them, the in-memory store is empty. HOWEVER, when the browser sends a request to TAPD, the server might return `Set-Cookie` headers, and the browser stores those cookies in memory.\n\nBut wait - how would the first navigation to TAPD succeed without the tapdsession cookie? It wouldn't. The server would redirect to login.\n\nUnless... the tapdsession cookie was correctly loaded from the database during browser startup. So Chromium CAN read Chrome's encrypted cookies.\n\nThen why the 0 cookies in the subsequent runs?\n\nLet me think... The first run was just before 12:00. At that time, 周以天 had just logged into TAPD in Chrome. I then killed Chrome and made a copy. The copy had the fresh tapdsession and other cookies. Chrome's Chromium could read them (because DPAPI works at the machine level).\n\nFor the subsequent runs, maybe:\n1. Chrome was writing to the profile during the copy\n2. The copy was made while some Chrome process was still running\n3. The `Cookies-journal` file indicates pending WAL writes to SQLite\n\nActually, in the subsequent runs, I killed Chrome BEFORE copying. But between killing Chrome and copying, Chrome might have written stale/invalid data to the cookies database during shutdown.\n\nWait, actually the last run (v5 with full robocopy) DID get Chrome killed first, and then made a copy. I killed Chrome at 12:01-something, then copied at 12:03:45. By then Chrome was fully shut down.\n\nBut there might be another issue: the `SingletonLock` file. When Chrome shuts down, it might leave lock files that confuse the next instance.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Instead of using lauchPersistentContext, let me directly read the SQLite database and parse the cookies. Since I know what data to look for, I can try to decrypt the cookies manually.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"看来 Playwright 读不了 Chrome 加密的 cookie。直接读 SQLite 数据库："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_08VWWg1YumXgkV8j3X0b3206","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"npm install --prefix C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace better-sqlite3 2>&1 | Select-Object -Last 3","timeout":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":88,"output":1077,"cacheRead":53504,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54669,"cost":{"input":0.00001232,"output":0.00030156000000000003,"cacheRead":0.001498112,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0018119920000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779249831963,"responseId":"a3057334-bb07-4229-9ab5-8c977fb00a4a"}}
