{"type":"message","id":"d5061fdc","parentId":"c7e187c0","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:10:58.437Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"System.Data.SQLite is not available. Let me try a different approach. I'll create a C# program that uses Microsoft.Data.Sqlite (which can be installed via NuGet) or use a COM-based approach.\n\nActually, wait. Let me try a completely different and much simpler approach. Instead of manually decrypting the cookies:\n\n1. Kill the current Chrome that's running\n2. Start Chrome fresh with `--remote-debugging-port=9222 --user-data-dir=<temp_copy_of_profile>`\n3. The temp copy already worked earlier (we got port 9222 listening)\n4. Use Playwright to connect to it\n5. This time, BEFORE the script navigates to TAPD, let's wait for Chrome to fully initialize\n\nActually the earlier attempt with the copied profile + remote debugging DID work (port 9222 was listening). But when I navigated to TAPD, it showed the login page. This means the cookies in the copied profile aren't valid for some reason.\n\nWait - I just realized something. When I copy the Chrome profile with robocopy, it copies the `Cookies` SQLite database. But this database contains encrypted data. When Chrome starts with this copied profile, it tries to decrypt the cookies using the key from Local State. But the encrypted cookies use a different encryption scheme (v20) that Chrome's internal code might not handle correctly either.\n\nActually no, Chrome v148 definitely can read its own cookies. The issue is that the profile copy might have some inconsistency.\n\nLet me try yet another approach. Instead of copying and using a separate Chrome process, let me just try to get the cookies directly from the running default Chrome process via CDP. Even though --remote-debugging-port=9222 didn't work, maybe there's another way.\n\nActually, you know what, let me just close Chrome, reopen it with --remote-debugging-port using a non-default user-data-dir, copy the profile properly, and try again. The earlier attempt failed because the copied profile had stale data.\n\nActually, I just had an idea. The v20 decryption is failing with \"wrong tag\" which means either:\n1. The AES key is correct but the data boundaries are wrong\n2. The AES key is wrong\n3. The encryption uses a different algorithm\n\nLet me first verify that the AES key is correct by trying to decrypt a different known Chrome data format. Or I can try to use the `chrome_cookies_decrypt` Python package via npx.\n\nActually, wait. Let me try another npm package that might work on Windows without native compilation.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_mJQpJMoHeXwcf9Rh0LvV3216","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace; npm install @fractalwrench/chrome-cookie-decoder 2>&1 | Select-Object -Last 3","timeout":20}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":96,"output":640,"cacheRead":90112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90848,"cost":{"input":0.00001344,"output":0.00017920000000000002,"cacheRead":0.002523136,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.002715776}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779250248944,"responseId":"7fa93bdd-e8f6-44dd-b129-d049ef208e52"}}
{"type":"message","id":"f27ae67f","parentId":"d5061fdc","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:10:59.637Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_mJQpJMoHeXwcf9Rh0LvV3216","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"npm error 404 Note that you can also install from a\r\nnpm error 404 tarball, folder, http url, or git url.\r\nnpm error A complete log of this run can be found in: C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\npm-cache\\_logs\\2026-05-20T04_1\r\n0_58_888Z-debug-0.log\n\n(Command exited with code 1)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":1,"durationMs":1184,"aggregated":"npm error 404 Note that you can also install from a\r\nnpm error 404 tarball, folder, http url, or git url.\r\nnpm error A complete log of this run can be found in: C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\npm-cache\\_logs\\2026-05-20T04_1\r\n0_58_888Z-debug-0.log\n\n(Command exited with code 1)","cwd":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779250259637}}
{"type":"message","id":"42e0b4fc","parentId":"f27ae67f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:11:03.970Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Not found. Let me try a different approach entirely. Let me compile and run a C# program that uses Microsoft.Data.Sqlite NuGet package.\n\nActually, we have node.js with better-sqlite3 already installed. The only issue is the AES decryption. Let me debug this more carefully.\n\nLet me check: when I ran the v2 script, it said:\n```\nAES Key length: 32 bytes\nAES Key hex: d4d8ac7d1c13348a2a8c...\n```\n\nBut the hex only shows 10 hex chars = 5 bytes. The full key might have issues.\n\nLet me also check: maybe Chrome 148 uses a different encryption for the encrypted_key in Local State. Maybe the key stored there is NOT the AES key but something else.\n\nLet me look at the Local State file more carefully for any additional crypto parameters.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_7UtFun3c5DSXAgT5vgFD4880","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"const fs = require('fs'); const s = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\AppData\\\\Local\\\\Google\\\\Chrome\\\\User Data\\\\Local State', 'utf8')); if (s.os_crypt) { console.log(JSON.stringify(s.os_crypt, null, 2).substring(0, 500)); } else { console.log('no os_crypt'); }\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":205,"output":319,"cacheRead":90752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":91276,"cost":{"input":0.000028700000000000003,"output":0.00008932,"cacheRead":0.002541056,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.002659076}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779250259639,"responseId":"dd81d9cc-d6d0-481f-bffb-67f0f43ddfc4"}}
