{"type":"message","id":"08388a09","parentId":"70b31ce2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:11:51.436Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the Playwright version on this system might also launch Chromium bundled with Playwright, which might not be able to read Chrome's app-bound encrypted cookies either.\n\nActually, thinking about it more carefully, the `app_bound_encrypted_key` is Chrome-specific. Playwright's bundled Chromium won't have the Chrome App Bound Encryption Service, so it can't decrypt the cookies.\n\nBut the first script DID work. So how?\n\nLet me re-examine: the first run was on the FIRST copy of the profile (right after killing Chrome). The profile at that time might have used OLD encryption (without app_bound_encrypted_key). But after Chrome restarted multiple times, it might have re-encrypted the cookies with the new app-bound key.\n\nOR... the first script only found 5 cookies including tapdsession with value \"17792496444cacb6af68c19f3f34be...\" - but maybe this was NOT the decrypted value. Maybe Playwright's Chromium partially read the database and returned the plaintext `value` field (which is empty for encrypted cookies) or the raw encrypted field.\n\nWait, looking at my first script code again:\n```javascript\nconst cookies = await context.cookies();\n```\n\nThis returns cookies from the Chromium context's cookie jar. If Chromium can't decrypt the cookies, they won't appear in the cookie jar. But the first run DID show them with values.\n\nHmm, but I also need to consider: maybe the first run was Chrome 147 or something, and between then and now, Chrome updated to 148 with the new encryption. No, the same session is being used.\n\nOK let me just try running it and see.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_rrPxqmDibnajyaqKg41P2167","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace; node scripts/extract_simple.mjs","timeout":90}}],"api":