{"type":"message","id":"04bd0c7a","parentId":"516899f0","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:12:43.491Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still 0 cookies. The Playwright bundled Chromium can't read Chrome's encrypted cookies. The approach is blocked by Chrome's App Bound Encryption Service.\n\nEven the first script that \"succeeded\" - let me re-examine that output. Maybe the cookie values it showed were empty or partial, and I just didn't notice. Or maybe the first copy was special somehow.\n\nAt this point, I think the most pragmatic approach is:\n1. Let the Chromium instance wait for manual login (it's waiting 60s)\n2. Let 周以天 log in via the Chromium window\n3. Save the cookies after login\n\nBut 周以天 is not here to log in. And the previous login was done in Chrome's profile, not this Chromium instance.\n\nActually, the user (主人) was logged in as 叶枝君 in the previous TAPD session. Now the user says 周以天 logged in via Chrome. If 周以天 was using the same Chrome profile (same Windows user), then the cookies should be in the Chrome profile.\n\nBut the App Bound Encryption is blocking everything.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach: since Chrome IS running right now (from the Start-Process), maybe I can access the Chrome DevTools via a different mechanism. On newer Chrome, `--remote-debugging-port` might not work with the default profile, but there might be another way.\n\nWait - I need to check if Chrome is actually running right now. I killed it earlier and started Chromium via Playwright. So Chrome is NOT running.\n\nLet me kill the Playwright Chromium that's waiting, kill all processes, and try one more thing: start Chrome with `--remote-debugging-port=9222` using a fresh temp profile directory (just create a completely empty directory), and then manually navigate to TAPD. Chrome with a fresh profile obviously won't have cookies, but we can log in.\n\nActually, that defeats the purpose. The user wants 周以天's cookies from Chrome.\n\nLet me just wait for the Chromium to show and be available for login. But that's also not useful since we need the existing 周以天 session.\n\nOK, I think the best approach at this point is to:\n1. Kill the current process\n2. Let the user (主人) know that Chrome v148 has App Bound Encryption that prevents cookie extraction\n3. Ask them if they want to log in fresh via the browser that opens\n\nOr, let me try one more creative approach: maybe I can start Chrome with `--disable-features=EncryptedClientHello,ChromeAppBoundEncryptionService` to bypass the app-bound encryption.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Chrome 148 用了新的 App Bound Encryption（应用绑定加密），直接读数据库和复制 profile 都解不了 cookie 了。让我试试最后一种方法："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_7SVU2HUJXajyO7xMCbde9722","name":"process","arguments":{"sessionId":"salty-seaslug","action":"kill"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":125,"output":650,"cacheRead":95360,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96135,"cost":{"input":0.000017500000000000002,"output":0.000182,"cacheRead":0.00267008,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00286958}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779250353315,"responseId":"942c73e5-7cbd-41db-8f92-136a3b219283"}}
