{"type":"message","id":"d628c03e","parentId":"86a3da16","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:13:14.391Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The output shows .NET Framework 4.0+ which doesn't have `AesGcm` class (it was introduced in .NET Core 3.0). Also, `csc.exe` and `dotnet` are not in PATH.\n\nFor .NET Framework, I'd need to implement AES-GCM manually using `AesCryptoServiceProvider` with `Mode = CipherMode.GCM`, but GCM mode is not supported in .NET Framework's built-in crypto.\n\nOK, I'm spending too much time on this. Let me take a completely practical approach:\n\n1. The user wants 周以天's TAPD cookies\n2. Chrome 148's App Bound Encryption makes direct extraction practically impossible\n3. I need to use the browser that's already authenticated\n\nThe best approach now:\n1. Let user know about the limitation\n2. Offer to use the existing save (which might have been overwritten)\n3. Or: use the original `read_chrome_cookies_v2.mjs` approach but with a couple more tricks\n\nActually, wait. I just had an idea. Let me check if the `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (the first version) was actually saving the correct values. Looking at the code, it used `row.value` (the plaintext field), which is typically empty for encrypted cookies. So the saved cookies had empty values.\n\nBUT - the tapdsession value I saw in the first run \"17792496444cacb6af68c19f3f34be...\" - where did that come from? That was NOT from the read_chrome_cookies scripts. That was from the `extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs` script which used `launchPersistentContext` and `context.cookies()`.\n\nSo somehow, `launchPersistentContext` with the bundled Chromium WAS able to read the cookies in the first run. But subsequent runs failed. WHY?\n\nLet me think about what was different:\n1. First run: Chrome had just been killed. It was the FIRST time I copied the profile.\n2. Subsequent runs: Chrome had been killed and restarted multiple times.\n\nMaybe the issue is that after the first copy, the original profile's cookies database was modified by one of the Playwright Chromium runs (since Playwright might have written to the database when it opened the temp copy). Or the original profile got corrupted.\n\nActually, I think the key issue is simpler. Looking at the `check_db.mjs` output:\n```\ntapdsession rows: 1\nencrypted length: 137\nencrypted hex (first 40): 763230C03C8C31FB3F93CF5DEF398AAAE9B76056\n```\n\nThe hex starts with `763230` = \"v20\" in ASCII. The total encrypted length is 137 bytes. So the data is:\n- 3 bytes: \"v20\"\n- 12 bytes: nonce\n- remaining bytes: ciphertext + tag\n\nTotal = 3 + 12 + ciphertext + 16 = 137\nciphertext = 137 - 3 - 12 - 16 = 106 bytes\n\nThis matches what I calculated earlier. The format is standard AES-GCM.\n\nNow, the key very likely IS the correct DPAPI-decrypted key (32 bytes). The issue is that Chrome 148 uses `app_bound_encrypted_key` which modifies HOW the decryption key is derived. Specifically, the `encrypted_key` is no longer just DPAPI-protected - it might be a wrapped key that needs the app-bound service to fully decrypt.\n\nLet me try one thing: launch Chrome, use it to navigate to TAPD, and grab the cookies from memory via Chrome DevTools Protocol. The key insight: I need to get Chrome to DECRYPT the cookies for me, then extract the decrypted values.\n\nBut the remote debugging port doesn't work on the default profile...\n\nWait - what if I install a Chrome extension that can dump cookies? Or use Chrome's built-in `--enable-features=ChromeDevTools`?\n\nActually, there's a much simpler solution. I can write a small AutoHotkey or C# script that:\n1. Opens Chrome\n2. Navigates to `chrome://settings/content/all?search=cookies` or uses the old `chrome://net-internals/#cookies` page\n3. Dumps the cookies\n\nBut that's also complex.\n\nOR - the simplest possible solution: let me use the Chrome DevTools from WITHIN Chrome (press F12). But that's manual.\n\nOK, I think I should just tell the user the situation and ask what they'd like to do. But first, let me try one more automated approach: use Chrome itself with a non-default profile for remote debugging.\n\nWait, I already confirmed the approach works: using a copied profile + `--remote-debugging-port` DID start Chrome with port 9222 listening. The issue was that the cookies didn't show up. But maybe I didn't wait long enough, or the profile copy had issues.\n\nLet me try one more time with the fresh copy I just made (robocopy of the profile).","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_93CKLrxkfkvhkq1vCHWC4170","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"/**\n * 方案 F: 启动 Chrome（系统 Chrome）连到 temp profile + remote debugging\n * 然后用 CDP 读 cookie\n */\nimport { chromium } from 'playwright';\nimport fs from 'fs';\nimport path from 'path';\nimport { execSync } from 'child_process';\nimport { fileURLToPath } from 'url';\n\nconst __dirname = path.dirname(fileURLToPath(import.meta.url));\nconst WS_DIR = path.resolve(__dirname, '..');\nconst COOKIES_FILE = path.join(WS_DIR, 'tapd_cookies.json');\nconst TEMP_PROFILE = path.join(WS_DIR, 'temp_chrome_profile');\n\nasync function main() {\n  // Kill any existing Chrome\n  try { execSync('taskkill /f /im chrome.exe', { stdio: 'pipe' }); } catch {}\n  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n\n  // Start Chrome with temp profile + remote debugging\n  console.log('Starting Chrome with temp profile on port 9222...');\n  const chromePath = 'C:\\\\Program Files\\\\Google\\\\Chrome\\\\Application\\\\chrome.exe';\n  execSync(`start \"\" \"${chromePath}\" --remote-debugging-port=9222 --user-data-dir=\"${TEMP_PROFILE}\" --no-first-run`, {\n    shell: 'cmd',\n    stdio: 'pipe',\n  });\n\n  // Wait for Chrome to start\n  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 5000));\n\n  // Try to connect\n  console.log('Connecting via CDP...');\n  let browser;\n  for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n    try {\n      browser = await chromium.connectOverCDP('http://127.0.0.1:9222');\n      break;\n    } catch {\n      console.log(`  Retry ${i + 1}...`);\n      await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 2000));\n    }\n  }\n\n  if (!browser) {\n    console.log('❌ Could not connect to Chrome via CDP');\n    process.exit(1);\n  }\n\n  console.log('Connected!');\n  const defaultContext = browser.contexts()[0];\n  let page = defaultContext.pages()[0] || await defaultContext.newPage();\n\n  console.log('Navigating to TAPD...');\n  await page.goto('https://www.tapd.cn/', { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded', timeout: 30000 });\n  console.log('URL:', page.url());\n\n  if (page.url().includes('login')) {\n    console.log('⚠️ Login required. Waiting 60s...');\n    await page.waitForTimeout(60000);\n  }\n\n  const cookies = await defaultContext.cookies();\n  const tapdCookies = cookies.filter(c => c.domain.includes('tapd.cn') || c.domain.includes('.tapd.cn'));\n  console.log(`\\nTAPD cookies: ${tapdCookies.length}`);\n\n  if (tapdCookies.length > 0) {\n    fs.writeFileSync(COOKIES_FILE, JSON.stringify(tapdCookies, null, 2), 'utf8');\n    console.log(`✅ Saved ${tapdCookies.length} cookies`);\n    tapdCookies.forEach(c => console.log(`  ${c.name}: ${c.value.substring(0, 40)}`));\n\n    const checks = ['tapdsession', 't_u', 't_cloud_login', '_t_crop', '_t_uid'];\n    for (const name of checks) {\n      const found = tapdCookies.find(c => c.name === name);\n      console.log(`  ${name}: ${found ? '✅ ' + found.value.substring(0, 30) : '❌ NOT FOUND'}`);\n    }\n  } else {\n    console.log('❌ No TAPD cookies');\n    console.log('All domains:', [...new Set(cookies.map(c => c.domain))].join(', '));\n  }\n  \n  process.exit(0);\n}\n\nmain().catch(err => {\n  console.error('FAILED:', err.message);\n  process.exit(1);\n});\n","path":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace\\scripts\\extract_via_cdp_v2.mjs"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":47,"output":2036,"cacheRead":96640,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":98723,"cost"