{"type":"message","id":"88d2087c","parentId":"50c491e5","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:13:28.227Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I have a problem. `execSync` with `start` and `shell: 'cmd'` will spawn a new process and immediately return. But the `start` command will return immediately anyway (it launches Chrome in the background).\n\nAlso, I need to make sure the temp_chrome_profile directory exists and is valid. I already copied it earlier.\n\nAlso, I realize now that my previous attempt at `extract_via_cdp.mjs` failed to connect to port 9222 because... wait, the earlier attempt with temp_cp DID work (got port 9222 listening). But then I killed Chrome and started the current one without remote debugging. So the port should be available.\n\nBut wait - the previous attempt used `Start-Process` from PowerShell which succeeded in connecting to port 9222 and extracting 0 TAPD cookies (because the profile cookies weren't readable by the copied instance).\n\nThe MAIN issue is: will Chrome with a COPIED profile be able to read the cookies using the App Bound Encryption Service? The answer is probably NO, because the app-bound service ties the encryption to the specific Chrome User Data directory path.\n\nSo ALL approaches involving copying the profile will fail with Chrome 148.\n\nThe ONLY approach that will work is reading cookies from the ORIGINAL Chrome profile while Chrome is running from the original location. But Chrome blocks remote debugging on the default profile.\n\nLet me check if there's a Chrome policy or flag to bypass this.\n\nActually, the user CHOSE to close Chrome earlier. Maybe they expected me to extract cookies BEFORE closing Chrome. But now Chrome is not running, and the profile is locked by encryption.\n\nGiven the situation, I think the most honest approach is to tell the user:\n\n1. Chrome 148 has new App Bound Encryption that prevents cookie extraction\n2. The current cookie file has outdated/empty cookies\n3. I need them to either:\n   a. Log in again via a fresh Playwright browser session (which I can open for them)\n   b. Or tell me another approach\n\nBut maybe I should try one more thing first: the `app_bound_encrypted_key` in Local State... maybe I can try to decrypt it as well using DPAPI.\n\nLooking at the `app_bound_encrypted_key`: \"\"\n\nBase64 decode → starts with \"APPB\" (not \"DPAPI\")\n\nThe `app_bound_encrypted_key` uses a different prefix and is handled by a separate Windows service. This is even harder to decrypt.\n\nOK, I'm going to give up on the automated extraction and tell the user the situation.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"这次 Chrome 148 的 App Bound Encryption 很顽固，cookie 完全解不出来 😅\n\n让我确认一下当前 `tapd_cookies.json` 的状态："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_b2eEgqKCGKf1NC2Ar0F18564","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"const fs = require('fs'); const c = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\\\\tapd_cookies.json')); console.log('Cookies count:', c.length); c.forEach(x => console.log(x.name, '=', x.value.substring(0, 30) || '(empty)'));\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":83,"output":990,"cacheRead":98688,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":99761,"cost":{"input":0.00001162,"output":0.0002772,"cacheRead":0.002763264,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.003052084}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779250394406,"responseId":"3cbe11fc-3232-4b27-802d-0d621b242f0b"}}
