{"type":"message","id":"19c7d741","parentId":"bb2fcc44","timestamp":"2026-05-20T04:13:54.108Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The `tapd_cookies.json` has 7 cookies, and the `tapdsession` value is NOT empty: `17792503160c843fcd5d91ae5d8ae9`. This was from the first successful extraction! These 7 cookies were saved from the `extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs` run.\n\nWait, but the first run saved 5 cookies. Then the `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (v2) saved 17 cookies with empty values. Then the `extract_via_cdp.mjs` or something else overwrote with 7 cookies.\n\nActually wait - let me check: the first `extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs` run saved 5 cookies including the REAL tapdsession. Then the v2 script (read_chrome_cookies_v2.mjs) saved 17 cookies with empty values (overwrote the file). But the current file has 7 cookies with a REAL tapdsession value.\n\nLet me think about where this came from. After the v2 script saved 17 empty cookies, I ran the CDP script (extract_via_cdp.mjs) which connected to port 9222 (temp_cp Chrome) and tried to navigate to TAPD. That script said \"Login required\" and waited 30s. But then... wait, I killed that session with `kill`. It might have saved cookies after the 30s wait.\n\nActually, looking at the session flow: the `extract_via_cdp.mjs` (nimble-ember) was polled and showed login page, then I killed it. So it shouldn't have saved anything.\n\nThen I ran `check_db.mjs` (which confirmed 1 tapdsession in DB). Then I ran the `extract_via_cdp_v2.mjs` (salty-seaslug) which got 0 initial cookies, navigated, got login page, waited 60s, and I killed it. So that shouldn't have saved anything either.\n\nSo where did the current tapd_cookies.json come from? It has 7 cookies with real values!\n\nWait, let me check: the `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` DID fail to decrypt but it saved cookies with `finalValue = row.value` as fallback. The `row.value` field (plaintext value in the database) is usually empty for encrypted cookies. But some cookies might have their value in the `value` field (not encrypted).\n\nLooking at the current cookies:\n- `tapdsession = 17792503160c843fcd5d91ae5d8ae9` - this IS a real tapdsession value! It's different from the first run (17792496...) because the session was updated.\n- `app_locale_name = zh_CN` - not encrypted\n- `sso-login-token = 33a88330a67df9d26e65c87b9625ed` - not encrypted\n- `__root_domain_v = .tapd.cn` - not encrypted\n- `_qddaz`, `_qdda`, `_qddab` - these are tracking cookies\n\nBut wait, I thought the v2 script saved empty values for all 17 cookies? Let me check the v2 script's output again:\n\n```\n  tapdsession (.tapd.cn): \n```\n\nThe value was empty for tapdsession. But the CURRENT file has a real value. So something must have overwritten it after the v2 script.\n\nOh wait! I just checked - I ran `extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs` (the FIRST script) which saved 5 cookies. Then I ran `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (the one with better-sqlite3 direct DB access) which saved the decrypted cookies. The first version of `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (not v2) saved cookies that had `finalValue = row.value` as fallback, and row.value for tapdsession was apparently NOT empty for the first read.\n\nWait, looking at the `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (original version, not v2):\n```javascript\nlet decryptedValue = decryptCookieValue(encB64, aesKey);\nconst finalValue = decryptedValue || row.value;\n```\n\nIf decryption failed (which it did - \"Unknown cookie version: v20\"), then `finalValue = row.value`. The `row.value` is the plaintext value column from the cookies table, which Chrome uses to store unencrypted cookie values.\n\nFor some cookies, the `value` column might have the actual value if Chrome determines the cookie doesn't need encryption. This is controlled by Chrome's encryption policy.\n\nSo looking at the current tapd_cookies.json, we actually DO have a valid tapdsession value! It's `17792503160c843fcd5d91ae5d8ae9...` (truncated at 30 chars).\n\nWait, but the v2 script (which ran later) also had the same fallback logic:\n```javascript\nlet finalValue = row.value || '';\n```\nAnd it showed empty values for everything. But then something overwrote the file...\n\nLet me think: after v2, which scripts ran?\n1. `extract_via_cdp.mjs` - connected to temp_cp Chrome, got login page, waited 30s, I killed it\n2. `extract_via_cdp_v2.mjs` - started new process, I killed it\n3. `check_db.mjs` - read-only, didn't write\n\nNone of these should have overwritten the file. But the v2 output showed empty values for tapdsession. Unless the v2 script was the one that saved them, and the output just showed the truncated empty display.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the v2 output:\n```\n  tapdsession (.tapd.cn): \n```\nThe value after the colon is empty/blank. That's `row.value || ''` = empty string. So row.value IS empty for tapdsession.\n\nBut the CURRENT file has a real tapdsession. This means either:\n1. It's the OLD file from the first successful run that wasn't overwritten\n2. Or something else wrote to it\n\nLet me check: was the current file overwritten by the CDP script (extract_via_cdp.mjs)? That script connected to Chrome, got 0 TAPD cookies, and wouldn't have saved anything. Unless... it navigated to TAPD, waited 30s, and SOMETHING happened.\n\nActually, I think I might have missed that the first successful extraction (extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs) saved 5 cookies with the real tapdsession value, and that file was NEVER overwritten. The subsequent scripts (read_chrome_cookies.mjs, read_chrome_cookies_v2.mjs) both used the SAME output filename, so they SHOULD have overwritten.\n\nUnless `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` (the original) DID succeed in getting the value from `row.value` (the plaintext column). Let me look at the original read_chrome_cookies.mjs output:\n```\n  tapdsession (.tapd.cn): \n```\nIt showed empty! But that's because `console.log(\\`  ${row.name} (${row.host_key}): ${finalValue.substring(0, 40)}\\`)` - if finalValue was empty, it would show nothing.\n\nBut the current file has a value... Something doesn't add up.\n\nActually, you know what, I think the read_chrome_cookies_v2.mjs might have accidentally saved the cookies with VALUES because of how the fallback logic worked. The `row.value || ''` for tapdsession might not be empty for cookies that were stored WITHOUT encryption.\n\nWait, tapdsession IS encrypted (we confirmed this). So `row.value` should be empty. Unless Chrome also stores the plaintext alongside the encrypted value.\n\nActually, in Chrome's cookie database, ALL cookies have BOTH a `value` field (plaintext, often empty) and an `encrypted_value` field (encrypted). For most cookies, the `value` field contains the actual cookie value. For SECURE or HTTPONLY cookies, Chrome might move the value to `encrypted_value` and leave `value` empty.\n\nSo for tapdsession (which is httpOnly), the actual value is ONLY in encrypted_value. The `value` field is empty.\n\nBut the CURRENT tapd_cookies.json has the tapdsession value. This must be from the FIRST run (extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs) which used `launchPersistentContext` with Chromium - Chromium was able to read the cookies and return them via `context.cookies()`.\n\nWait, but then `read_chrome_cookies.mjs` and `read_chrome_cookies_v2.mjs` both overwrote the file...\n\nLet me just check: is the current tapd_cookies.json value the same as what the first run showed?\n\nFirst run showed: `17792496444cacb6af68c19f3f34be...`\nCurrent file shows: `17792503160c843fcd5d91ae5d8ae9` (truncated at 30 chars)\n\nWait, the current one is truncated at 30 chars: `17792503160c843fcd5d91ae5d8ae9` - this is different from the first run (`17792496444cacb6...`). So they ARE different. Maybe the first run saved a subset of cookies, and then another script added more?\n\nActually, let me just read the full current file to see.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"等等，当前 `tapd_cookies.json` 