{"type":"message","id":"18817209","parentId":"04c36b25","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:07:34.916Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"user:ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b6fe0a0b350b8b370430f9a52dc0\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"sender\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-05-20 14:04 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Yousan(叶枝君) (ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"name\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b6fe0a0b350b8b370430f9a52dc0]\nYousan(叶枝君): 验证码窗口无法通过机器人检测, 还有什么办法能直接从chrome中解析cookie吗"}],"timestamp":1779257244521}}
{"type":"message","id":"4469342a","parentId":"18817209","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:07:56.959Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying that the Playwright browser window with the TAPD login QR code is being detected as a bot (WAF blocking). They're asking if there's another way to extract cookies directly from Chrome.\n\nPreviously, we tried several approaches:\n1. `launchPersistentContext` with a copied Chrome profile - failed because Chromium can't decrypt Chrome's v20 + App Bound encrypted cookies\n2. Direct SQLite reading - AES-GCM decryption failed with \"v20\" format and App Bound Encryption\n3. Chrome with `--remote-debugging-port` on the default profile - blocked by Chrome's security\n4. Chrome with copied profile + remote debugging - port worked but cookies were not available (App Bound Encryption)\n5. `chrome-cookies-secure` npm package - failed because `win-dpapi` native module needs node-gyp\n\nBut wait - option 3 worked partially! When I used Chrome with a COPIED profile + `--remote-debugging-port=9222`, I was able to connect via CDP. The issue was that the cookies didn't show up. But maybe the issue was timing - Chrome needs time to load its cookies.\n\nActually, let me rethink. The App Bound Encryption is handled by a Windows service. When Chrome starts with a COPIED profile directory, the encryption key is tied to the ORIGINAL profile path. So Chrome with a copied profile CAN'T decrypt the cookies because the app-bound key is bound to the original `C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\Google\\Chrome\\User Data` path.\n\nThe ONLY Chrome that can decrypt the cookies is Chrome running from the ORIGINAL profile path. But Chrome blocks remote debugging on the default profile.\n\nWait - unless I can:\n1. Start Chrome normally (from its original default profile)\n2. Open the DevTools\n3. Extract cookies via DevTools console\n\nActually, there's a much simpler approach I haven't tried: **Chrome DevTools Protocol via piping**. Chrome can expose its DevTools through a file-based pipe instead of a TCP socket. This might bypass the \"default profile + remote debugging\" restriction.\n\nActually, that's not right either.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user wants to extract cookies from the ORIGINAL Chrome profile. Chrome is currently... let me check if Chrome is running. The login script (tidy-reef) opened a Playwright Chromium browser, not Chrome. So Chrome (the original application) is probably NOT running.\n\nHere's another idea: **Start the real Chrome (not Playwright Chromium) with the ORIGINAL profile AND with remote debugging enabled, but using a pipe instead of a TCP port**. \n\nActually, Chrome on Windows supports `--remote-debugging-pipe` which establishes a debugging connection via stdin/stdout pipe. This might bypass the \"default profile restriction.\"\n\nBut actually, the error we got earlier was:\n```\nDevTools remote debugging requires a non-default data directory.\n```\n\nThis means Chrome blocks ANY form of remote debugging on the default profile. This is a deliberate security feature.\n\nOK here's another approach: what if I can use Chrome's **command-line** to launch with a custom flag that lets me access the debugging port? The flag might be different in newer Chrome versions.\n\nActually, wait. I just remembered something. The first `Start-Process` with `--remote-debugging-port=9222` DID show Chrome processes with that flag. But the port wasn't listening. This might be because Chrome started and detected that the profile was in an inconsistent state (after my Chrome killing and experiments), so it didn't fully start.\n\nLet me try a cleaner approach:\n1. Kill ALL Chrome and Chromium processes\n2. Remove ALL lock files from the default Chrome profile\n3. Start Chrome normally (without any special flags) - this will do a clean start\n4. Then close Chrome\n5. Start Chrome again with `--remote-debugging-port=9222`\n\nActually, Chrome might cache the fact that it was previously started with `--remote-debugging-port` in its profile preferences.\n\nHmm, let me think about another approach entirely.\n\n**What about launching Chrome via `--utility-cmd-prefix` or using the `chrome.debugger` API?**\n\nNo, that won't work.\n\n**What about using a Chrome extension?**\n\nI could install a Chrome extension that exports cookies, but extensions can't access cookies from other extensions or Chrome's internal pages easily.\n\n**What about using the `chrome://net-export` or `chrome://net-internals`?**\n\nNo, those don't export cookies.\n\n**What about using `--enable-logging` to capture Chrome's network traffic including cookies?**\n\nThe cookies might appear in Chrome's net logs when it sends requests. I could:\n1. Kill Chrome\n2. Start Chrome with `--enable-logging --v=1` or similar\n3. Navigate to TAPD (from the Chrome that just started, which has access to the cookies)\n4. Extract cookies from the log files\n\nThis is actually promising! Chrome's net logs might include the cookie headers.\n\nActually wait, there's an even better approach. Chrome has a built-in **netlog** at `chrome://net-internals/#events`. You can capture network events there and export them. But this requires manual interaction.\n\nLet me think about `--log-net-log` flag. Chrome can capture ALL network events to a file:\n```\nchrome.exe --log-net-log=C:\\path\\to\\netlog.json\n```\n\nThen when Chrome opens TAPD, the request headers (including cookies) are logged. Let me try this!\n\nActually, this logs the events but might not include cookie values since they're stripped from logs for privacy. Let me check...\n\nActually, there's another flag: `--net-log-capture-mode=IncludeSensitive` which includes cookie values in the net logs.\n\nLet me try:\n1. Kill all Chrome\n2. Start Chrome with `--log-net-log=C:\\path\\to\\netlog.json --net-log-capture-mode=IncludeSensitive`\n3. Chrome navigates to its start page (which will be whatever was last open, hopefully TAPD)\n4. Wait for Chrome to load TAPD\n5. Read the netlog JSON file\n6. Extract cookies from the logged HTTP headers\n\nThis might work!\n\nActually, the simpler approach might be to start Chrome, wait for it to load, have it navigate to TAPD, and then read the netlog.\n\nBut I need to control Chrome - what URL it navigates to. I can use `--` after the flags to specify a URL.\n\nLet me try:\n```\nchrome.exe --log-net-log=C:\\path\\to\\netlog.json --net-log-capture-mode=IncludeSensitive https://www.tapd.cn/\n```\n\nThis should:\n1. Start Chrome with the original profile (able to decrypt cookies)\n2. Navigate to TAPD\n3. Log ALL network traffic including cookies\n4. I read the netlog and extract the cookies\n\nThis is brilliant! Let me try it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"回来！有个新思路——用 Chrome 的 netlog 抓取网络请求中的 cookie 头 🎯"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_FasvtuYKdZlw5ruVQ5jU8162","name":"process","arguments":{"sessionId":"tidy-reef","action":"kill"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":11516,"output":1564,"cacheRead":98304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111384,"cost":{"input":0.00161224,"output":0.00043792,"cacheRead":0.002752512,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004802672}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779257254917,"responseId":"87f63ec6-fa6f-4e59-9592-1ed3067c20e4"}}
