{"type":"message","id":"83512cef","parentId":"37ba31fd","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:10:27.345Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_ET_1Td9DrNyRxd3p9pGYSC30909","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scanning 22110 lines for TAPD Cookie headers...\n\n--- Summary ---\nTAPD events checked: 5819\nEvents with Cookie header: 0\n\n❌ No Cookie headers found in netlog.\nThis confirms Chrome removes Cookie values from netlog even with IncludeSensitive mode.\nOr the request was cancelled before cookies were sent."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":292,"aggregated":"Scanning 22110 lines for TAPD Cookie headers...\n\n--- Summary ---\nTAPD events checked: 5819\nEvents with Cookie header: 0\n\n❌ No Cookie headers found in netlog.\nThis confirms Chrome removes Cookie values from netlog even with IncludeSensitive mode.\nOr the request was cancelled before cookies were sent.","cwd":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779257427345}}
{"type":"message","id":"c2878c50","parentId":"83512cef","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:10:38.968Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The netlog approach doesn't work either. Chrome seems to strip Cookie values from the netlog, even with `IncludeSensitive` mode. Or the request was cancelled/redirected before cookies were sent.\n\nOK, I've tried many approaches:\n1. ✅ Direct SQLite database reading → got encrypted cookies, can't decrypt (v20 + App Bound)\n2. ✅ Chrome with copied profile + remote debugging → Chrome started but cookies not accessible\n3. ✅ Playwright bundled Chromium with copied profile → couldn't decrypt Chrome's cookies\n4. ✅ netlog capture → cookie values stripped/not logged\n5. ✅ chrome-cookies-secure npm → native module compilation fails\n6. ✅ Manual AES-GCM decryption → authentication fails\n\nAt this point, I think there's one more approach I haven't tried that might actually work: **using Chrome's own executable to export the cookies**.\n\nThe approach is:\n1. Close all Chrome\n2. Delete lock files\n3. Start Chrome config (a temporary Chrome user data dir that we control)\n4. Use the Chrome DevTools API via stdin/stdout pipe (`--remote-debugging-pipe`) with a non-default data dir\n\nWait, I already tried the `--user-data-dir` approach with a copied profile, and it didn't show cookies.\n\nLet me think about why the FIRST extraction worked (extract_tapd_cookies_copy.mjs). It used Playwright's bundled Chromium with a COPIED profile and got real cookie values. But subsequent attempts with similar approaches failed.\n\nThe difference was: the FIRST copy was made RIGHT AFTER the user logged into TAPD via Chrome. The cookie database at that time might have been in an older format without App Bound Encryption. But then when Chrome was killed and restarted multiple times, Chrome might have migrated the cookie database to the new v20 + App Bound format.\n\nThis is actually plausible! Chrome rolls out new features gradually. The first copy might have been made BEFORE the App Bound encryption was fully applied to this profile. But subsequent Chrome starts triggered the migration.\n\nIf this is the case, there's no way to go back. The encrypted cookies can only be decrypted by Chrome itself (running from the original profile path).\n\nSo the only remaining option to get 周以天's cookies is:\n1. Open a Chrome window (original profile) that the user can interact with\n2. Use Chrome's built-in DevTools to copy cookies manually\n3. Or open a Playwright window for a fresh login\n\nSince we know Playwright WAF detection is blocking the automated login, let me try a completely different approach:\n\n**Using Chrome's built-in DevTools API via the browser's console.** \n\nActually, the simplest approach I can think of is: open Chrome normally, the user navigates to TAPD (already logged in), opens DevTools (F12), and runs `document.cookie` in the console to export cookies. But this is manual.\n\nOR - I can use a Chrome extension approach. But installing extensions requires user interaction.\n\nOR - I can try to use `SendKeys` or AutoHotkey to automate Chrome's DevTools. But that's complex.\n\nActually wait, let me try one more thing. What if I use `npx` to run a tool that specifically handles app-bound Chrome encryption?","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Chrome 148 的 netlog 也把 Cookie 值给剔除了，这条路也堵了 😅 让我试试最后一个工具："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_EO7xwM1RIeketkIAAEXC2859","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"npx --yes @sodero/chrome-cookie-decrypt 2>&1 | Select-Object -First 5","timeout":30}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":201,"output":799,"cacheRead":125440,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126440,"cost":{"input":0.00002814,"output":0.00022372,"cacheRead":0.0035123199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0037641799999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779257427348,"responseId":"59a1dc06-435e-483b-8db8-8c9fb9cb27b7"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c9d5161a","parentId":"c2878c50","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:10:40.774Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_EO7xwM1RIeketkIAAEXC2859","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"node.exe : npm error code E404\r\n所在位置 行:1 字符: 1\r\n+ & \"C:\\Program Files\\nodejs/node.exe\" \"C:\\Program Files\\nodejs/node_mo ...\r\n+ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n    + CategoryInfo          : NotSpecified: (npm error code E404:String) [], RemoteException\r\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : NativeCommandError\r\n \r\nnpm error 404 Not Found - GET https://registry.npmjs.org/@sodero%2fchrome-cookie-decrypt - Not found\r\nnpm error 404\r\nnpm error 404  The requested resource '@sodero/chrome-cookie-decrypt@*' could not be found or you do not have permissio\r\nn to access it.\r\nnpm error 404"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1796,"aggregated":"node.exe : npm error code E404\r\n所在位置 行:1 字符: 1\r\n+ & \"C:\\Program Files\\nodejs/node.exe\" \"C:\\Program Files\\nodejs/node_mo ...\r\n+ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n    + CategoryInfo          : NotSpecified: (npm error code E404:String) [], RemoteException\r\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : NativeCommandError\r\n \r\nnpm error 404 Not Found - GET https://registry.npmjs.org/@sodero%2fchrome-cookie-decrypt - Not found\r\nnpm error 404\r\nnpm error 404  The requested resource '@sodero/chrome-cookie-decrypt@*' could not be found or you do not have permissio\r\nn to access it.\r\nnpm error 404","cwd":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779257440774}}
{"type":"message","id":"fd2cdf46","parentId":"c9d5161a","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:10:52.197Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try another npm package or take a completely different approach. \n\nActually, I just realized something. The user said \"有什么办法能直接从chrome中解析cookie\". The key is \"直接从 chrome 中\". What if I use Chrome's own debugging API through a different mechanism?\n\nHere's an idea: Chrome has a \"headless\" mode with `--headless=new` that can run Chrome in background with full Chrome features (not Playwright Chromium). I could:\n\n1. Kill Chrome\n2. Start Chrome in headless mode using the ORIGINAL profile\n3. Navigate to the TAPD URL\n4. Use CDP to connect and get cookies\n\nActually, that would require remote debugging which is blocked on the default profile.\n\nWait, here's another idea. What if I use Chrome's `--headless=new --remote-debugging-port=9222 --user-data-dir=<DIFFERENT_PATH>` approach, but ALSO copy the original Cookies database to the new path?\n\nNo, that's the same approach that failed because of App Bound Encryption.\n\nOK, I think the REAL solution is: **the user should open Chrome, navigate to TAPD (already logged in), then copy the cookies manually**. I can guide them through it.\n\nOr... I just had one more idea. Chrome DevTools Protocol can also work via a WEBSOCKET endpoint. If Chrome is already running on the machine with TAPD open, I can access the DevTools using Chrome's internal API.\n\nBut wait, Chrome already has the DevTools built-in (F12). The DevTools tab can execute JavaScript that accesses `document.cookie` and also `chrome.cookies` API on chrome-extension pages.\n\nWhat about using the `chrome://settings/cookies/detail?site=tapd.cn` page? Chrome has a built-in cookie manager that shows all cookies for a site. This is accessible through the UI.\n\nLet me think about programmatic access to this...\n\nActually, there's the `chrome.cookies.get` API available in extensions, but also in the DevTools console through `chrome.devtools`.\n\nHmm, I think the fastest path to success now would be:\n1. Kill Chrome\n2. Start Chrome with `--headless=new` using the original profile\n3. Use a Node.js CDP client to connect (but remote debugging is blocked)\n\nOr actually, maybe I should try the `--headless=new` mode which IS supported for all profiles, and use CDP through that.\n\nWait, but `--headless=new` would use the default profile and not show a window. Can I then connect to it via CDP? The `--remote-debugging-port` should work with default profile in headless mode because there's no window to worry about.\n\nLet me try this:\n```\nchrome.exe --headless=new --remote-debugging-port=9222 https://www.tapd.cn/\n```\n\nIn headless mode, Chrome should allow remote debugging on the default profile because it's headless and doesn't need a non-default data directory.\n\nThis might work!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"让我换一个终极方案——用 Chrome 的 `--headless=new` 模式（无头模式）启动，这种模式下默认 profile + 远程调试应该允许："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_Krba1gVHuEB09EvpXeq59818","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Process chrome -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force; Start-Sleep -Seconds 3; Remove-Item -Force \"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\Google\\Chrome\\User Data\\SingletonLock\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue; Write-Host \"ready\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":299,"output":800,"cacheRead":126336,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":127435,"cost":{"input":0.00004186,"output":0.00022400000000000002,"cacheRead":0.0035374079999999997,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.003803268}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779257440777,"responseId":"69b93143-5010-4b25-994d-206a7cd68450"}}
