{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"user:ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b6fe1550bd480b3ecb38d1a7b91b\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"sender\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-05-20 14:16 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Yousan(叶枝君) (ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"name\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"b773dd22","parentId":"fa31a40d","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:16:33.373Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"de4402a4","parentId":"b773dd22","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:16:52.237Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user installed a Cookie Editor Chrome extension. They want me to control Chrome to export the cookies. Since Chrome is already running (the user is using it), I can use Playwright's CDP to connect to Chrome.\n\nBut earlier we couldn't connect via CDP because Chrome doesn't have `--remote-debugging-port` enabled. However, there might be a way to connect to Chrome if we close it and restart with the debugging port.\n\nWait, actually - the user says they installed a cookie editor extension. They want ME to automate the process of copying cookies. But the issue is Chrome doesn't have remote debugging enabled on the default profile.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user has Chrome open with the cookie editor extension installed. They want me to:\n1. Somehow control Chrome to extract cookies\n2. Or use the cookie editor extension\n\nSince Chrome is running and I can't connect via CDP (no debugging port), I need another approach.\n\nActually, wait. Let me check if Chrome has a remote debugging endpoint available. If Chrome was started normally (without flags), there's no way to connect via CDP.\n\nBut the user just installed an extension. Extensions DO have access to `chrome.debugger` API which allows them to attach to pages. But I can't control extensions programmatically.\n\nHmm, let me think about what the user actually means. They installed a cookie editor Chrome extension. The extension can show/edit cookies. Maybe they want me to guide them through using it? Or they want me to write a script that somehow gets the cookies?\n\nActually, I think the most practical approach is: since the user has a cookie editor extension that can export cookies, I should guide them to use it. But the user asked \"你能操作码\" (can you operate it?) - they want ME to do it.\n\nThe only way I can \"operate\" Chrome is if Chrome has remote debugging enabled. Since there's no remote debugging, I can't.\n\nBUT - here's an idea. Let me check if Chrome is currently running. If it is, I can:\n1. Kill Chrome\n2. Restart Chrome with `--remote-debugging-port=9222`\n3. Then use Playwright CDP to connect and extract cookies via the cookie editor extension or DevTools\n\nBut we know `--remote-debugging-port` doesn't work on the default profile. Even `--headless=new` didn't work.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. The user says they installed the cookie editor extension. Maybe I can use the extension's API or a known method to extract cookies.\n\nWait, actually there's a much simpler approach I haven't tried! **Use Chrome's own JavaScript console via a cdp approach with `--remote-allow-origins=*` and have Chrome already running.**\n\nNo, that still needs the debugging port.\n\nOK, let me think about this differently. The user wants me to extract cookies. They're willing to help by installing an extension. What if I:\n\n1. Write a simple Node.js script that uses `npx` or Puppeteer to start Chrome with `--remote-debugging-port` on a NEW profile (temp)\n2. Copy the cookie database from the original Chrome profile to this temp profile\n3. ... but this fails because of App Bound Encryption\n\nOR:\n\n1. Close Chrome\n2. Start a headless Chrome instance with a temp profile AND with the original user data directory symlinked/hardlinked\n3. Then the App Bound Encryption would work because the encryption is bound to the profile path\n\nWait, that's clever! What if I:\n1. Kill Chrome\n2. Create a hardlink or symlink to the original user data directory at a different path\n3. Start Chrome with `--user-data-dir=<symlink_path>` and `--remote-debugging-port=9222`\n4. Since the data directory has the same content (same files), App Bound Encryption should work\n5. Connect via CDP and extract cookies\n\nActually, a symlink to the original directory would work because:\n- Chrome uses the profile path in the App Bound key derivation\n- If I symlink C:\\MyTemp to C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\AppData\\Local\\Google\\Chrome\\User Data\n- Chrome sees C:\\MyTemp as the path (not the default one)\n- But the files are the same, so the encryption key works\n- And remote debugging is allowed because it's not the default directory\n\nLet me try this approach!\n\nActually, I need to be more precise. The `--remote-debugging-port` restriction is specifically about the default data directory path. If I use a different path (even a symlink to the same directory), it should be allowed. But the App Bound Encryption key is tied to the original profile path, so Chrome might not be able to decrypt cookies if the path changes.\n\nHmm, actually that's the problem. The App Bound Encryption key is specifically bound to the ORIGINAL profile path. If Chrome starts with a symlink to the same directory, it might:\n1. See the path as different (e.g., C:\\MyTemp instead of C:\\Users\\...\\User Data)\n2. Try to decrypt using the NEW path as part of the key\n3. Fail because the key was encrypted for the ORIGINAL path\n\nSo this approach won't work either.\n\nOK, let me try the simplest thing first. Let me check if Chrome is running, and if so, try a DIFFERENT approach to CDP.\n\nActually, let me try using `Microsoft Edge WebDriver` approach. No, that's different.\n\nWhat about the `chrome.debugger` API in a Chrome extension? If the cookie editor extension has permission to access cookies, maybe its internal API can be called programmatically?\n\nThis is getting too complex. Let me just ask the user to manually export the cookies using the cookie editor extension and paste them to me. That's the fastest path to success.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"主人，装了 Cookie Editor 的话最快的方式是：\n\n**你手动导出，粘贴给我就行：**\n1. Chrome 打开 TAPD（保持登录状态）\n2. 点 Cookie Editor 扩展图标\n3. 选导出（Export / 全部导出）\n4. 复制导出内容粘贴给我\n\n我收到后直接写入 `tapd_cookies.json`～ 这样最靠谱 🎯\n\n如果非要我来操作的话，我需要先杀 Chrome 再以远程调试模式启动，但 Chrome 148 默认 profile 不让开调试端口……所以手动导出最快了。"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":307,"output":1365,"cacheRead":131584,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":133256,"cost":{"input":0.000042980000000000005,"output":0.0003822,"cacheRead":0.003684352,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004109532}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1779257793374,"responseId":"3b3dc0d3-2c36-4fc6-8ba6-25cdbd325d1b"}}
