{"type":"message","id":"f9ddb223","parentId":"6d7ff684","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:37:06.742Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No password in data.kv either. The password is stored as an SRP (Secure Remote Password) verifier in config.yaml, which is a cryptographic hash. You can't recover the original password from it.\n\nHFS v3 doesn't store passwords in plaintext - it uses SRP protocol which means:\n1. The password is used to generate an SRP verifier on first setup\n2. Only the verifier (hash) is stored\n3. When logging in, the client proves knowledge of the password using SRP protocol without sending the password itself\n4. The password CANNOT be recovered from the verifier\n\nHowever, there are a few things I can try:\n1. Check if there's a `debug.log` that might contain the password\n2. Check the old-hfs.exe version which might use a different config format\n3. Check if there are any environment variables or startup scripts that contain the password\n4. Look for any notes or passwords stored nearby\n\nLet me also check the old-hfs.exe and the debug.log.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_Izm3PcXg3EOEC9TkFnP43768","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Content \"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\Downloads\\hfs\\debug.log\" -Encoding UTF8 -Tail 50"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":745,"output":285,"cacheRead":154112,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":155142,"cost":{"input":0.0001043,"output":0.0000798,"cacheRead":0.004315136,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004499236}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779259021798,"responseId":"13cee3fd-a859-487c-8636-8f0b72e10e60"}}
