{"type":"message","id":"02855792","parentId":"b36d311d","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:56:40.202Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"HFS started and the `--cli passwd admin` was treated as invalid command. The approach of piping to the CLI didn't work.\n\nLooking at the output, HFS started serving on port 80. I can access the web admin interface at `http://192.168.95.85/~/admin/` and log in with the old password... but we don't know the old password.\n\nLet me try a different approach. I'll modify the config.yaml to remove the password (delete the accounts section), which will make HFS start without authentication, then the user can set a new password from the web UI.\n\nActually, wait - HFS is now running (it started successfully). Let me stop it first, then modify the config.\n\nActually, I already have a simpler approach. Let me modify the config.yaml to remove the SRP verifier, which effectively removes password protection on the admin account. Then the user can set a new password from the admin panel.\n\nOr better yet, let me use HFS's built-in API to change the password. Since HFS is running on port 80, I could potentially use the API.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: modify config to remove the password, restart HFS.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_osyzUsjE8jtZ9XVaBc5j7254","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Process hfs -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Stop-Process -Force; Start-Sleep -Seconds 2; Write-Host \"stopped\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":515,"output":343,"cacheRead":157568,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":158426,"cost":{"input":0.0000721,"output":0.00009604000000000001,"cacheRead":0.0044119039999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004580043999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779260195416,"responseId":"67dc46fb-fb58-4e2b-9e85-30254ae71dbf"}}
