{"type":"message","id":"5be4be2e","parentId":"6d398e71","timestamp":"2026-05-20T07:29:25.604Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the `D:\\cdn_solo\\` directory exists and has content (Log, Temp, update, Version, README.md). The VFS looks correct.\n\nThe netstat command didn't output anything (or it's the pipe issue). Let me check what port HFS is listening on by looking at the process command line or by trying to access it.\n\nActually, looking at the debug.log, I see:\n- `http port 80 busy: hfs.exe` - first instance tried port 80 but it was busy\n- `http port 8000 busy: hfs.exe` - second instance tried port 8000 but busy\n\nThis suggests HFS couldn't bind to port 80 (because another HFS was already running on it). The first HFS (started at 14:58) grabbed port 80. The second one (14:59) tried 8000 but that might also be busy or taken.\n\nBut wait - maybe the first HFS instance that I killed earlier was the original one serving on port 80. When I killed it and started a new one, the new HFS might have used a different port.\n\nLet me check what ports are actually listening.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_HbUGqJ35IQP27z54KUTl0153","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"netstat -ano | Select-String \"LISTEN\" | Select-String \":80 |:8000 |:443 \" 2>&1; Write-Host \"===\"; Get-CimInstance Win32_Process -Filter \"Name = 'hfs.exe'\" | Select-Object ProcessId, @{N=\"Port\";E={(Get-NetTCPConnection -OwningProcess $_.ProcessId -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object -First 1).LocalPort}}","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":572,"output":409,"cacheRead":170240,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":171221,"cost":{"input":0.00008008,"output":0.00011452000000000001,"cacheRead":0.0047667199999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.004961319999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779262158740,"responseId":"863bbfee-bbe8-41e