{"type":"message","id":"2ad09336","parentId":"51035f8a","timestamp":"2026-05-20T07:29:37.902Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So:\n- HFS process 32904 (the one I started via Start-Process at 14:58) - no port bound! It couldn't bind to port 80 (busy).\n- HFS process 15724 (started at 14:59 from the CLI attempt) - port 8000\n\nThe process 32904 (the one I originally started) couldn't bind to port 80 because something else is using it. And process 15724 bound to port 8000.\n\nWait, but the logs say \"http port 80 busy: hfs.exe\" for process 32904. Then process 15724 says \"http port 8000 busy: hfs.exe\". But looking at netstat, process 15724 IS bound to port 8000. So the \"busy\" message might mean it was busy in a previous attempt before successfully binding.\n\nActually wait - let me read the debug.log again:\n```\n2026-05-20 14:56:16 - Invalid command, try 'help'     ← first CLI attempt (killed)\n2026-05-20 15:00:00 - http port 80 busy: hfs.exe      ← my Start-Process attempt (couldn't get port 80)\n2026-05-20 15:28:09 - http port 8000 busy: hfs.exe    ← another instance tried port 8000\n```\n\nSo the current HFS on port 8000 (PID 15724) is the one from the CLI attempt. The one I started via Start-Process (PID 32904) couldn't get port 80.\n\nBut the real question: why can't resources be downloaded? Let me try to access HFS.\n\nAlso, the user said \"无法下载资源\". This might be because:\n1. HFS is on port 8000 but the user is trying to access port 80\n2. The HFS service path or configuration changed\n3. There are permission issues with the files\n\nLet me check:\n1. Which port the original HFS was serving on\n2. If port 80 is being used by something else\n3. If the file serving works","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_hSfSISv1YThh3Sg6wL3q4683","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 检查 80 端口谁占了\nnetstat -ano | Select-String \":80 \" | Select-String \"LISTEN\" 2>&1; Write-Host \"===\"; # 试一下 H